<HEADLINE>
ROC REP OFFICE TO SEND STAFF TO VIRGINIA TECH TO EXTEND
CONDOLENCES
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Washington,  April 18 (CNA) 04/19/07  13:26:20 (By Lin Chieh-yu
and Sofia Wu)
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's representative office in the United States said
Wednesday it will send staff members to Virginia Tech University
the following day to extend condolences after Monday's shooting
rampage which claimed 33 lives, including the gunman's.
</P>
<P>
The officials from the Republic of China representative office in
Washington, D.C. will also meet with Taiwanese students and
faculty members at the Virginia Tech campus in Blacksburg,
Virginia where the deadliest campus massacre in U.S. history took
place, an office spokesman said, adding that if necessary, the
officials will offer assistance to them.
</P>
<P>
The representative office already sent condolence messages to
Virginia Tech management by phone on behalf of the ROC government
and people shortly after the tragedy, the spokesman said, adding
that the office also immediately contacted the school's
international student affairs division and the Taiwanese Students
Association to get confirmation that all Taiwanese students and
professors were safe and unharmed.
</P>
<P>
Celine Lin, president of the Taiwanese Students Association of
Virginia Tech, posted a report on the group's Web site Tuesday
saying that each of the Taiwan students and faculty, totaling
some 60, had been contacted by phone to establish that they were
safe and well.
</P>
<P>
In Taipei, Ministry of Foreign Affairs spokesman Wang Chien-yeh
also expressed his sympathies and condolences at a routine news
conference Tuesday on behalf of the ROC government over the
tragic incident.
</P>
<P>
ROC Representative to U.S. Joseph Wu has also made phone calls to
the Virginia State  Government,  State  Assembly  and federal
congressional members from the state to express his condolences,
said Pi Tsu-an,  a secretary at the ROC representative  office in
Washington, D.C. The ROC's Education Minister Tu Cheng-sheng has
also faxed a condolence letter to Virginia Tech University
President Charles W. Steger, Pi said.
</P>
<P>
When the representative office staff members visit the school
Thursday, Pi said, they will pass on a condolence letter from Wu
to the school's management.
</P>
